<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	our ability to increase our productivity and capacity.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Forward-looking statements are usually accompanied by words such as "anticipate," "believe," "estimate," "may," "might," "intend," &#8220;interest,&#8221; "appear," "expect," &#8220;suggest,&#8221; &#8220;plan,&#8221; &#8220;encourage,&#8221; &#8220;potential&#8221; and similar expressions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Actual results could differ materially from historical results or those implied by the forward-looking statements contained in this report.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Undue reliance should not be placed on our forward-looking statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Except as required by law, we undertake no obligation to update or announce any revisions to forward-looking statements contained in this report, whether as a result of new information, future events or otherwise.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Current Market Conditions
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Demand for our products and services to the oil refining and chemical industries depends on capital investment for new capacity, retrofit and debottlenecking projects and for planned or unplanned maintenance activity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Increased volatility and significant reduction in global crude oil prices beginning in the second half of calendar 2014 has caused uncertainty in the oil refining and chemical industries.&nbsp;&nbsp;The dramatic reduction and increased volatility in global crude oil prices has caused a significant slowdown in investment by our oil refining and chemical industry customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;These markets have altered their investment timing over the past year due to this sustained lower price and volatility of crude oil.&nbsp;&nbsp;Capital investment within global refining and chemical industries contracted during fiscal 2016 compared with fiscal 2015 and is projected to be down further in fiscal 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the near term, we believe that the catalyst for increased investment would likely be higher or more stable crude oil prices.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, if crude oil prices remain low for a sustained period, we expect increased global energy demand would eventually drive additional investment regardless of crude oil prices.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	19
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage20"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU19">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Demand for our products and services in the nuclear power utility market is affected by investment in maintenance, repair, life extension and nuclear regulatory mandated investment along with global investment in new capacity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Global investment in new cap
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	acity is affected by regional legislative policy and comparative cost per unit of power output with other energy sources, such as natural gas, oil or alternative energies. Although the nuclear market which we serve is very fragmented, we continue to believ
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	e that it provides an important opportunity for our growth, especially via market share gains.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our naval nuclear propulsion market has demand tied to aircraft carrier and submarine vessel construction schedules of the primary shipyards who service the U.S. Navy.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect growth in our naval nuclear propulsion business based on our strategic actions to increase our market share and expected demand.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Strategic investment and continued concentration of effort on oil refining and chemical markets will have a long-term perspective, notwithstanding the severity of the current downturn in these markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that long-term demand drivers for energy requirements are unchanged and have not been affected by the recent price of crude oil.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that such demand, which is driven by population growth and an expanding middle class in emerging markets, requires an increase in global energy capacity and investment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our strategy is to continue to leverage our investments and expand our capabilities and execution capacity to grow market share in the oil refining, chemical and nuclear markets, as well as our business with the U.S. Navy.&nbsp;&nbsp;For more information, refer to the heading &#8220;Strategy and Outlook&#8221; within this Item 7 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe the long-term outlook in our key markets supports our strategy to grow our revenue to over $200,000 across the next business cycle in our markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the near term, new order levels are expected to remain volatile, resulting in both relatively strong and weak periods.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The chart below shows the impact of our diversification strategy.&nbsp;&nbsp; Over 60% of our backlog at the end of fiscal year 2016 is from markets not served in the Fiscal 2007-2009 time frame.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:1PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Fiscal 2016 Compared with Fiscal 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Sales for fiscal 2016 were $90,039, down $45,130 or 33%, as compared with sales of $135,169 for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Domestic sales were $57,027 or 63% of total sales, down from $86,399 or 64% of total sales in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Domestic sales decreased $29,372, or 34%, compared with fiscal 2015 across all end markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;International sales accounted for $33,012 or 37% of total sales for fiscal 2016, down from $48,770, or 36%, of total sales in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;International sales decreased $15,758, or 32%, compared with fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;All international markets were weaker, with the largest decreases occurring in Canada, South and Central America and Asia.&nbsp;&nbsp;By market, sales for fiscal 2016 were 32% to the refining industry, the same as in fiscal 2015, 33% to the chemical and petrochemical industries, down from 35% in fiscal 2015, 16% to the power markets, up from 15% in fiscal 2015, and 19% to defense and other industrial applications, up from 18% in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our gross margin for fiscal 2016 was 25.8% compared with 30.9% for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The reduction in gross margin was driven by (1) lower facility utilization due to the 33% reduction in sales; (2) a very competitive pricing environment; and (3) costs incurred ahead of revenue for our Navy and nuclear strategies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross profit for fiscal 2016 decreased $18,549, or 44% compared with fiscal 2015 due to lower sales volume as well as the items which affected gross margin.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Selling, general and administrative, or SG&amp;A, expense for fiscal 2016 was $16,565, down 11% or $1,947, compared with $18,512 in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;SG&amp;A as a percentage of sales in fiscal 2016 increased to 18.4% of sales compared with 13.7% of sales in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase as a percent of sales was due to lower sales levels in fiscal 2016, partly offset by cost reductions.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the prior year, fiscal 2015, we also incurred a pre-tax restructuring charge of $1,718 ($1,164 after tax) for severance costs related largely to a voluntary early retirement program we offered in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015 and to certain involuntary headcount reductions which occurred in the same quarter.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cost reductions in fiscal 2016 SG&amp;A were partly due to this restructuring as well as lower selling, commission and other compensation expenses related to lower sales and earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Other income in fiscal 2016 was $1,789.&nbsp;&nbsp;This was due to cancellation fees received from customers primarily for two orders totaling $7,168 which were cancelled in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;There was no other income in fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Interest income for fiscal 2016 was $261, up from $189 in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense for fiscal 2016 was $10 compared with $11 in fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our effective tax rate in fiscal 2016 was 30% compared with an effective tax rate of 32% for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;This decrease in rates was due to the retroactive reinstatement of the R&amp;D tax credit.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Net income for fiscal 2016 and income per diluted share was $6,131 and $0.61, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Net income in fiscal 2015 was $14,735 or $1.45 per diluted share, and excluding the impact of the restructuring charge, was $15,899 and $1.57, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Fiscal 2015 Compared with Fiscal 2014
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Sales for fiscal 2015 were $135,169, up $32,951 or 32%, as compared with sales of $102,218 for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Domestic sales were $86,399 or 64% of total sales, up from $63,850 or 62% of total sales in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Domestic sales increased $22,549, or 35%, compared with fiscal 2014 driven principally by new capacity investment in the U.S. chemical industry.&nbsp;&nbsp;International sales accounted for $48,770 or 36% of total sales for fiscal 2015, up from $38,368, or 38%, of total sales in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;International sales increased $10,402, or 27%, compared with fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;By market, sales for fiscal 2015 were 32% to the refining industry, down from 35% in fiscal 2014, 35% to the chemical and petrochemical industries, up from 24% in fiscal 2014, 15% to the power markets, down from 23% in fiscal 2014, and 18% to defense and other industrial applications, the same as in fiscal 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU21">
</A>
	Our gross margin for fiscal 2015 was 30.9% compared with 31.1% for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Leverage from 33% greater revenue in 2015 versus 2014 was muted by lower pricing for certain orders and the extent of subcontracting that was required due to timing of
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	21
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage22"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	customer requirements and near-term capacity li
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	mitations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross profit for fiscal 2015 increased $9,992, or 31% compared with fiscal 2014 due to higher sales volume.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Selling, general and administrative, or SG&amp;A, expense for fiscal 2015 was $18,512, up 8% or $1,317, compared with $17,195 in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, SG&amp;A as a percentage of sales in fiscal 2015 was 13.7% of sales compared with 16.8% of sales in fiscal 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We incurred a pre-tax restructuring charge of $1,718 ($1,164 after tax) for severance costs related largely to a voluntary early retirement program we offered in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015 and to certain involuntary headcount reductions which occurred in the same quarter.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our reduction in headcount was approximately 10% of our global workforce.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately 20% of the headcount reductions occurred in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The remaining headcount reductions occurred in the first four months of fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The expected annual savings from these reductions was approximately $3,000, of which $2,000 was realized in fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Interest income for fiscal 2015 was $189, up from $94 in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense for fiscal 2015 was $11 compared with $1 in fiscal 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our effective tax rate in fiscal 2015 was 32% compared with an effective tax rate of 31% for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Net income for fiscal 2015 and income per diluted share was $14,735 and $1.45, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Net income, excluding the impact of the restructuring charge, was $15,899 or $1.57 per diluted share, up 57% compared with $10,145 and $1.00, respectively, in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Stockholders&#8217; Equity
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The following discussion should be read in conjunction with our consolidated statements of changes in stockholders&#8217; equity that can be found in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table shows the balance of stockholders' equity on the dates indicated:
</P>

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Fiscal 2016 Compared with Fiscal 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Stockholders&#8217; equity decreased $7,171 or 6%, at March 31, 2016 compared with March 31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;This decrease was primarily due to our repurchase of 539 shares at a cost of $9,441, partially offset by net income earned in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Item 5 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K for more information on our stock repurchase program.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On March 31, 2016, our net book value per share was $11.34, down 1% over March 31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Fiscal 2015 Compared with Fiscal 2014
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Stockholders&#8217; equity increased $10,643 or 10%, at March 31, 2015 compared with March 31, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;This increase was primarily due to our income earned in fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On March 31, 2015, our net book value per share was $11.50, up 10% over March 31, 2014.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:1PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:6PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	(1)&nbsp;&nbsp;Working capital equals current assets minus current liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	(2)&nbsp;&nbsp;Working capital ratio equals current assets divided by current liabilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We use the above ratios to measure our liquidity and overall financial strength.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:6PT;COLOR:#FF0000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;TEXT-INDENT:2.59%;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:36PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	Net cash generated by operating activities for fiscal 2016 was $18,751, compared with $6,279 for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash generated from changes in unbilled revenues, customer deposits, and accounts receivables reversed cash usage in those categories in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;These were partially offset by lower net income, and decreases in accounts payable and accrued compensation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Capital spending in fiscal 2016 was $1,153, compared with $5,300 in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fiscal 2015 capital spending included the capital expansion at our Batavia, NY manufacturing facility, which started in the middle of fiscal 2014 and was completed in the middle of fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;This expansion was to support our growth strategies in the refining, petrochemical and for the U.S. Navy markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Capital expenditures in fiscal 2016 were approximately 90% for facilities along with machinery and equipment and the remaining 10% for all other items.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:6PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;TEXT-INDENT:2.59%;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:36PT;">
	Share repurchases of $9,441, to repurchase 539 shares, and dividend payments of $3,296 occurred in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;There w
</FONT>
	ere no share repurchases in fiscal 2015 and dividend payments were $2,026.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Cash and investments were $65,072 on March 31, 2016 compared with $60,271 on March 31, 2015, up $4,801 or 8%.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We invest net cash generated from operations in excess of cash held for near-term needs in short-term, less than 365 days, certificates of deposit, money market accounts or U.S. government instruments, generally with maturity periods of up to 180 days.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our money market account is used to securitize our outstanding letters of credit, which reduces our cost on those letters of credit.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately 95% of our cash and investments is held in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;The remaining 5% is invested in our China operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Capital expenditures for fiscal 2017 are expected to be between approximately $2,000 and $2,500.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately 85% of our fiscal 2017 capital expenditures are expected to be for machinery and equipment, with the remaining amounts expected to be used for other items.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On December 2, 2015, we entered into a new senior revolving credit facility agreement with JP Morgan Chase Bank, N.A.&nbsp;&nbsp;This revolving credit facility replaced our previous facility, which was with Bank of America, N.A.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new facility is of equivalent size as the one it replaced, providing us with a line of credit of $25,000, including letters of credit and bank guarantees.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, our JP Morgan Chase agreement allows us to increase the line of credit, at our discretion, up to another $25,000, for total availability of $50,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;Borrowings under this credit facility are secured by all of our assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also have a $5,000 unsecured line of credit with HSBC, N.A.&nbsp;&nbsp;Letters of credit outstanding on March 31, 2016 and March 31, 2015 were $11,982 and $10,903, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The outstanding letters of credit as of March 31, 2016 were issued by JP Morgan Chase, HSBC, as well as Bank of America, under our previous credit facility.&nbsp;&nbsp;JP Morgan letters of credit were $1,749 and HSBC letters of credit were $1,921 on March 31, 2016. Bank of America letters of credit were $8,312 on March 31, 2016 and were cash secured.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bank of America letters of credit do not reduce the availability on our credit facility with JP Morgan Chase.&nbsp;&nbsp;The borrowing rate under our JP Morgan Chase facility as of March 31, 2016 was the bank&#8217;s prime rate, or 3.50%.&nbsp;&nbsp;Availability under the JP Morgan Chase and HSBC lines of credit was $26,330 at March 31, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The availability under the Bank of America and HSBC lines, which were in place, on March 31, 2015, was $19,097.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that cash generated from operations, combined with our investments and available financing capacity under our credit facility, will be adequate both to meet our cash needs for the immediate future and to support our growth strategies.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Contractual Obligations
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As of March 31, 2016, our contractual and commercial obligations for the next five fiscal years ending March 31 and thereafter were as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	Amounts represent anticipated contributions during fiscal 2016 to our postretirement medical benefit plan, which provides healthcare benefits for eligible retirees and eligible survivors of retirees.&nbsp;&nbsp;On February 4, 2003, we terminated postretirement healthcare benefits for our U.S. employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Benefits payable to retirees of record on April 1, 2003 remained unchanged.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect to be required to make cash contributions in connection with these plans beyond one year, but such amounts cannot be estimated.&nbsp;&nbsp;No contributions are expected to be made to our defined benefit pension plan for fiscal 2017.

</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:-4.54%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Orders and Backlog
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:-4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Orders in fiscal 2016 decreased 38% to $83,997 from $136,533 in fiscal 2015, net of $12,095 of cancellations which occurred in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Orders represent communications received from customers requesting us to supply products and services.&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenue is recognized on orders received in accordance with our revenue recognition policy described in Note 1 to the consolidated financial statements contained in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Domestic orders were 67%, or $56,383, and international orders were 33%, or $27,614, of our total orders in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;This compared to domestic orders of $92,115, or 67%, of total orders, and international orders of $44,418, or 33%, of our total orders in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp; Domestic orders decreased by $35,732, or 39%.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015 there was a large U.S. Navy order, which did not repeat in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, there was lower demand in the refining and petrochemical processing industries, partly offset by increased power orders.&nbsp;&nbsp;International orders decreased by $16,804, or 38%, due to decreases in orders from and cancellations from Canada.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Backlog was $107,963 at March 31, 2016, down 5% compared with $113,811 at March 31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Backlog is defined by us as the total dollar value of orders received for which revenue has not yet been recognized.&nbsp;&nbsp;All orders in backlog represent orders from our traditional markets in established product lines.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately 45% to 55% of orders currently in our backlog are expected to be converted to sales within one year.&nbsp;&nbsp;At March 31, 2016, approximately 21% of our backlog was attributed to equipment for refinery project work, 11% for chemical and petrochemical projects, 17% for power, including nuclear energy, 47% for U.S. Navy projects and 4% for other industrial or commercial applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;At March 31, 2015, approximately 24% of our backlog was for refinery project work, 15% for chemical and petrochemical projects, 9% for power, including nuclear energy, 48% for U.S. Navy projects and 4% for other industrial or commercial applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;At March 31, 2016, we had two projects for $6,466 on hold.&nbsp;&nbsp;We had three projects totaling $12,095 cancelled in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015, we had two projects for $5,895 cancelled.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Strategy and Outlook
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Continued weakness in the global energy markets is expected to impact our business in fiscal 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;The decrease in orders, and multiple cancellations, which occurred in fiscal 2016 I expected to lead to a challenging fiscal 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our pipeline has contracted as our oil refining and chemical market customers further reduced their capital spending plans when compared with last year in reaction to low and volatile oil prices.&nbsp;&nbsp;The expected duration of this downturn is uncertain.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect to see strength in our power business as our power orders in fiscal 2016 improved compared with fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Despite the current downturn, we continue to believe in the long-term strength of the energy markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Coupled with our diversification strategy with the U.S. Navy and the power market, we believe this long-term strength will support our strategy to significantly grow our business when the energy markets recover.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have invested in capacity to serve our commercial customers as well as to expand the work we do for the U.S. Navy.&nbsp;&nbsp;We intend to continue to look for organic growth opportunities as well as acquisitions or other business combinations that we believe will allow us to expand our presence in both our existing and ancillary markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are focused on reducing earnings volatility, growing our business and diversifying our business and product lines.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU23">
</A>
	The headwinds in the energy markets have caused near term uncertainty.&nbsp;&nbsp;This has affected our outlook for fiscal 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect revenue in fiscal 2017 to be approximately $80,000 to $95,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;We project that approximately 45% to 55% of our March 31,
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	24
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage25"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2016 backlog will convert to sales in fiscal 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect the remaining backlog will convert beyond fiscal 2017, which includes a combination of U.S. Navy orders
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	that have a long conversion cycle (up to five years) as well as certain commercial orders the conversion of which has been extended by our customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We expect gross profit margin in fiscal 2017 to be in the 24% to 26% range, compared with 25.8% in fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect continued pricing pressure and under-utilization of our production facilities in fiscal 2017. We believe that production overhead absorption will be weak, which we expect in turn will put pressure on gross profit margins.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	SG&amp;A spending during fiscal 2017 is expected to be between $17,500 and $18,500, or approximately 19% and 20% of sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our effective tax rate during fiscal 2017 is expected to be between 32% and 33%.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We expect that cash flow in fiscal 2017 will be much more moderate than fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fiscal 2016 cash flow benefited from the build-up of accounts receivable and unbilled revenue which occurred in the latter portion of fiscal 2015 and was converted to cash in fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We continue to believe that the long-term outlook for the energy markets is strong.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will continue to look toward future growth while being mindful of near term profitability, given short-term challenges.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Contingencies and Commitments
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have been named as a defendant in lawsuits alleging personal injury from exposure to asbestos allegedly contained in, or accompanying, our products.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are a co-defendant with numerous other defendants in these lawsuits and intend to vigorously defend ourselves against these claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;The claims are similar to previous asbestos lawsuits that named us as a defendant.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such previous lawsuits either were dismissed when it was shown that we had not supplied products to the plaintiffs&#8217; places of work or were settled by us for immaterial amounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As of March 31, 2016, we are subject to the claims noted above, as well as other legal proceedings and potential claims that have arisen in the ordinary course of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although the outcome of the lawsuits to which we are, or may become, a party to cannot be determined and an estimate of the reasonably possible loss or range of loss cannot be made, we do not believe that the outcomes, either individually or in the aggregate, will have a material effect on our results of operations, financial position or cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Critical Accounting Policies
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The discussion and analysis of our financial condition and results of operations are based upon the consolidated financial statements and the notes to consolidated financial statements included in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K, which have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Critical accounting policies are defined as those that reflect significant judgments and uncertainties, and could potentially result in materially different results under different assumptions and conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Revenue Recognition.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We recognize revenue on all contracts with a planned manufacturing process in excess of four weeks (which approximates 575 direct labor hours) using the percentage-of-completion method.&nbsp;&nbsp;The majority of our revenue is recognized under this methodology.&nbsp;&nbsp;The percentage-of-completion method is determined by comparing actual labor incurred as of a specific date to our estimate of the total labor to be incurred on each contract or completion of operational milestones assigned to each contract.&nbsp;&nbsp;Contracts in progress are reviewed monthly, and sales and earnings are adjusted in current accounting periods based on revisions in the contract value and estimated material and labor costs at completion.&nbsp;&nbsp;Losses on contracts are recognized immediately, when evident to management.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Revenue on contracts not accounted for using the percentage-of-completion method is recognized utilizing the completed contract method.&nbsp;&nbsp;The majority of the contracts we enter into have a planned manufacturing process of less than four weeks and the results reported under this method do not vary materially from the percentage-of-completion method.&nbsp;&nbsp;We recognize revenue and all related costs on the completed contract method upon substantial completion or shipment of products to the customer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Substantial completion is consistently defined as at least 95% complete with regard to direct labor hours.&nbsp;&nbsp;Customer acceptance is required throughout the construction process and we have no further material obligations under the contracts after the revenue is recognized.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU24">
</A>
	Valuation of Goodwill and Intangible Assets.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Assets and liabilities acquired in a business combination are recorded at their estimated fair values at the acquisition date.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair value of identifiable intangible assets is based upon detailed valuations that use various assumptions made by management.&nbsp;&nbsp;Goodwill is recorded when the purchase price exceeds the estimated fair value of the net identifiable tangible and intangible assets acquired.&nbsp;&nbsp;Definite lived intangible assets are amortized over their estimated useful lives and
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	25
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage26"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	are assessed for impairment if cert
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	ain indicators are present.&nbsp;&nbsp;Goodwill and intangible assets deemed to have indefinite lives are not amortized but are subject to impairment testing annually or earlier if an event or change in circumstances indicates that the fair value of a reporting unit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	may have been reduced below its carrying value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Pension and Postretirement Benefits.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Defined benefit pension and other postretirement benefit costs and obligations are dependent on actuarial assumptions used in calculating such amounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;These assumptions are reviewed annually and include the discount rate, long-term expected rate of return on plan assets, salary growth, healthcare cost trend rate and other economic and demographic factors.&nbsp;&nbsp;We base the discount rate assumption for our plans on Moody's or Citigroup Pension Liability Index AA-rated corporate long-term bond yield rate.&nbsp;&nbsp;The long-term expected rate of return on plan assets is based on the plan&#8217;s asset allocation, historical returns and expectations as to future returns that are expected to be realized over the estimated remaining life of the plan liabilities that will be funded with the plan assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;The salary growth assumptions are determined based on long-term actual experience and future and near-term outlook.&nbsp;&nbsp;The healthcare cost trend rate assumptions are based on historical cost and payment data, the near-term outlook, and an assessment of likely long-term trends.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Income Taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We use the liability method to account for income taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under this method, deferred tax liabilities and assets are recognized for the tax effects of temporary differences between the financial reporting and tax bases of liabilities and assets measured using the enacted tax rate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Deferred income tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the difference between the financial statement and tax bases of assets and liabilities using current tax rates.&nbsp;&nbsp;We evaluate available information about future taxable income and other possible sources of realization of deferred income tax assets and record valuation allowances to reduce deferred income tax assets to an amount that represents our best estimates of the amounts of such deferred income tax assets that more likely than not will be realized.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The calculation of our tax liabilities involves dealing with uncertainties in the application of complex tax regulations. Significant judgment is required in evaluating our tax positions and determining our provision for income taxes. During the ordinary course of business, there are many transactions and calculations for which the ultimate tax determination is uncertain. We establish reserves for uncertain tax positions when we believe that certain tax positions do not meet the more likely than not threshold. We adjust these reserves in light of changing facts and circumstances, such as the outcome of a tax audit or the lapse of the statute of limitations. The provision for income taxes includes the impact of reserve provisions and changes to the reserves that are considered appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Critical Accounting Estimates and Judgments
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have evaluated the accounting policies used in the preparation of the consolidated financial statements and the notes to consolidated financial statements included in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K and believe those policies to be reasonable and appropriate.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that the most critical accounting estimates used in the preparation of our consolidated financial statements relate to labor hour estimates and establishment of operational milestones which are used to recognize revenue under the percentage-of-completion method, fair value estimates of goodwill and identifiable tangible and intangible assets acquired in business combinations, accounting for contingencies, under which we accrue a loss when it is probable that a liability has been incurred and the amount can be reasonably estimated, and accounting for pensions and other postretirement benefits.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As discussed above under the heading "Critical Accounting Policies," we recognize a majority of our revenue using the percentage-of-completion method.&nbsp;&nbsp;The key estimate of percentage-of-completion accounting is total labor to be incurred on each contract and to the extent that this estimate changes, it may significantly impact revenue recognized in each period.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We base the fair value of identifiable tangible and intangible assets on detailed valuations that use information and assumptions provided by management.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair values of the assets acquired and liabilities assumed are determined using one of three valuation approaches: market, income or cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;The selection of a particular method for a given asset depends on the reliability of available data and the nature of the asset.&nbsp;&nbsp;The market approach values the asset based on available market pricing for comparable assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;The income approach values the asset based on the present value of cash flows projected to be generated by that asset.&nbsp;&nbsp;The projected cash flows are discounted at a required rate of return that reflects the relative risk of the transaction and the time value of money.&nbsp;&nbsp;The projected cash flows for each asset considers multiple factors, including current revenue from existing customers, the high cost barrier to entry of markets, and expected profit margins giving consideration to historical and expected margins.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cost approach values the asset by determining the current cost of replacing that asset with another of equivalent economic utility.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cost to replace the asset reflects the replacement cost, less an allowance for loss in value due to depreciation or obsolescence, with specific consideration given to economic obsolescence if indicated.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	26
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage27"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU25">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Contingencies, by their nature, relate to uncertainties that require us to exercise judgment both in assessing the likelihood that a liability has been incurred
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	as well as in estimating the amount of potential loss.&nbsp;&nbsp;For more information on these matters see the notes to consolidated financial statements included in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Accounting for pensions and other postretirement benefits involves estimating the cost of benefits to be provided well into the future and attributing that cost over the time period each employee works.&nbsp;&nbsp;To accomplish this, extensive use is made of assumptions about inflation, investment returns, mortality, turnover, medical costs and discount rates.&nbsp;&nbsp;These assumptions are reviewed annually.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The discount rate used in accounting for pensions and other postretirement benefits expense (income) is determined in conjunction with our actuary by reference to a current yield curve and by considering the timing and amount of projected future benefit payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;The discount rate assumption for fiscal 2016 was 3.74% for our defined benefit pension plan and 3.11% for our other postretirement benefit plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;A reduction in the discount rate of 50 basis points, with all other assumptions held constant, would have increased fiscal 2016 net periodic benefit expense for our defined benefit pension plan and other postretirement benefit plan by approximately $840 and $0, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The expected return on plan assets assumption of 8.0% used in accounting for our pension plan is determined by evaluating the mix of investments that comprise plan assets and external forecasts of future long-term investment returns.&nbsp;&nbsp;A reduction in the rate of return of 50 basis points, with other assumptions held constant, would have increased fiscal 2016 net periodic pension expense by approximately $199.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	During fiscal 2016, the pension plan released liabilities for vested benefits of certain participants through the purchase of nonparticipating annuity contracts with a third party insurance company.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of this transaction, the projected benefit obligation and plan assets decreased $1,710 and $1,798, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As part of our ongoing financial reporting process, a collaborative effort is undertaken involving our managers with functional responsibilities for financial, credit, tax, engineering, manufacturing and benefit matters, and outside advisors such as lawyers, consultants and actuaries.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that the results of this effort provide management with the necessary information on which to base their judgments and to develop the estimates and assumptions used to prepare the financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that the amounts recorded in the consolidated financial statements included in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K related to revenue, contingencies, pensions, other postretirement benefits and other matters requiring the use of estimates and judgments are reasonable, although actual outcomes could differ materially from our estimates.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	New Accounting Pronouncements
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the normal course of business, management evaluates all new accounting pronouncements issued by the Financial Accounting Standards Board, the SEC, the Emerging Issues Task Force, the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants or any other authoritative accounting body to determine the potential impact they may have on our consolidated financial statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;For discussion of the newly issued accounting pronouncements see &#8220;Accounting and reporting changes&#8221; in Note 1 to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 of Part II of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Off Balance Sheet Arrangements
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We did not have any off balance sheet arrangements as of March 31, 2016 or March 31, 2015, other than operating leases and letters of credit incurred in the ordinary course of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
</EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:5PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM_ITEM_7A">
</A>
	Item 7A.&nbsp;&nbsp; Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The principal market risks (i.e., the risk of loss arising from market changes) to which we are exposed are foreign currency exchange rates, price risk and project cancellation risk.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The assumptions applied in preparing the following qualitative and quantitative disclosures regarding foreign currency exchange rate, price risk and project cancellation risk are based upon volatility ranges experienced by us in relevant historical periods, our current knowledge of the marketplace, and our judgment of the probability of future volatility based upon the historical trends and economic conditions of the markets in which we operate.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	27
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage28"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="GHM-10K_20160331_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU26">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Foreign Currency
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	International consolidated sales for fiscal 2016 were 37% of total sales, down from 36% of sales in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating in markets throughout the world exposes us to movements in currency exchange rates.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currency movements can affect sales in several ways, the foremost being our ability to compete for orders against foreign competitors that base their prices on relatively weaker currencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Business lost due to competition for orders against competitors using a relatively weaker currency cannot be quantified.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, cash can be adversely impacted by the conversion of sales made by us in a foreign currency to U.S. dollars.&nbsp;&nbsp;In each of fiscal 2016, fiscal 2015, and fiscal 2014, substantially all sales for which we or our subsidiaries were paid were denominated in the local currency (U.S. dollars or Chinese RMB).&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have limited exposure to foreign currency purchases.&nbsp;&nbsp;In each of fiscal 2016, fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014, our purchases in foreign currencies represented 1% of the cost of products sold.&nbsp;&nbsp;At certain times, we may enter into forward foreign currency exchange agreements to hedge our exposure against potential unfavorable changes in foreign currency values on significant sales and purchase contracts negotiated in foreign currencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Forward foreign currency exchange contracts were not used in fiscal 2016 or fiscal 2015, and as of March 31, 2016 and 2015, respectively, we held no forward foreign currency contracts.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Price Risk
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Operating in a global marketplace requires us to compete with other global manufacturers which, in some instances, benefit from lower production costs and more favorable economic conditions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although we believe that our customers differentiate our products on the basis of our manufacturing quality and engineering experience and excellence, among other things, such lower production costs and more favorable economic conditions mean that certain of our competitors are able to offer products similar to ours at lower prices.&nbsp;&nbsp;In extreme market downturns, such as we are currently experiencing, we typically see depressed price levels.&nbsp;&nbsp;Moreover, the cost of metals and other materials used in our products have experienced significant volatility.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such factors, in addition to the global effects of the recent volatility and disruption of the capital and credit markets, have resulted in downward demand and pricing pressure on our products.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Project Cancellation and Project Continuation Risk
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Adverse economic or specific project conditions can lead to a project being placed on hold or cancelled by our customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2016, we had three projects totaling $12,095, which were cancelled.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015, we had two projects totaling $5,895 cancelled.&nbsp;&nbsp;At March 31, 2016, we had two projects for $6,466 on hold
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We attempt to mitigate the risk
</FONT>
	of cancellation by structuring contracts with our customers to maximize the likelihood that progress payments made to us for individual projects cover the costs we have incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, we do not believe we have a significant cash exposure to projects which may be cancelled.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Open orders are reviewed continuously through communications with customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;If it becomes evident to us that a project is delayed well beyond its original shipment date, management will move the project into "placed on hold" (i.e., suspended) category.&nbsp;&nbsp;Furthermore, if a project is cancelled by our customer, it is removed from our backlog.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	28
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
</EFX_MARKET_RISK>
